title: $A falls ahead of US jobs figures
text:
Fri, Oct 2, 2015, 5:37 PM AEST - Australia Markets closed $A falls ahead of US jobs figures AAP – 14 minutes ago Print 
The Australian dollar is weaker ahead of the release of key US jobs data that may influence the timing of a Federal Reserve rate hike. 
At 1700 AEST on Friday, the local unit was trading at 70.46 US cents, down from 70.64 cents on Thursday. 
The fall came despite a modest rise after the release of local retail spending figures, which showed a rise 0.4 per cent in August, in line with economists' expectations. 
But investor caution ahead of key US employment figures due on Friday night weighed on the Aussie dollar during afternoon trade, IG Markets analyst Angus Nicholson said. 
"Traders are preparing for a good number to come out of the US non-farm payrolls tonight," he said. 
"A strong number we will likely see the Aussie dollar weaken against the US dollar." 
He said the US jobs numbers may shed more light on the chances of the US Federal Reserve raising its benchmark interest rate in December. 
Analysts expect the report will show the US economy added 205,000 jobs in September, and an unchanged unemployment rate of 5.1 per cent, a seven-year low. 
At 1700 AEST, one Australian dollar was buying 84.56 Japanese yen, down from 84.86 on Thursday, and 63.06 euro cents, down from 63.39 euro cents. 
Meanwhile, the Australian bond market is flat. 
At 1630 AEST on Friday, the December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.345 (implying a yield of 2.655 per cent), unchanged from Thursday.
